quran[7]{c,v,t}:
  45,1,"Ha, Mîm."
  45,2,"The bestowal of the Scripture from on high is by Allah the Almighty, the All-Wise."
  45,3,"Indeed, in the heavens and the earth are signs for the believers."
  45,4,"And in your<a class=""sup""><sup>pl </sup></a>own creation, and in the treading creatures He scatters, are signs for people who believe with certitude."
  45,5,"And the alternation of night and day, and the provision Allah has sent down from the sky, with which He has revived the earth after its death, and the shifting of the <span class="h">winds{1}</span>are signs for people who reason.",footnotes:1:<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: Hamza, Al-Kesa’i and Khalaf read it as: “wind”.</span>
  45,6,"Those are Allah’s signs{1}which We read to you<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>in truth. So in which discourse, after Allah and His signs, <span class="h">will they{2}</span><span class=""h"">believe</span>?",footnotes:1:[The Arabic word used is a<i>yat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.],footnotes:2:[<span class="qiraat-footnote">Qira’at: All except for Nafie’, Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr, Hafs, Abu Ja’far and Rouh read it as: “…will you<sup><small>pl</small></sup> believe?”</span>]
  45,7,"Woe to every sinful liar"
  45,8,"who hears Allah’s signs<a class=""sup""><sup>b </sup></a>being read to him, yet he persists arrogantly, as though he did not hear them. So give<a class=""sup""><sup>sg </sup></a>him glad tidings{1}of a painful punishment.",footnotes:1:This is said in sarcasm.
  45,9,"And when he learns something of Our signs, he takes them in mockery; for those{1}is a demeaning punishment.",footnotes:1:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
  45,10,"Beyond them lies Hell, and what they have earned will not benefit them at all, nor will those whom they took as guardians apart from Allah, and for them is a great punishment."
